<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0132</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DDB0132</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stoke-on-Trent City Council – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Please accept this letter as the full and considered response to the current call for written evidence in relation to the draft Deregulation Bill from Stoke-on-Trent City Council. We are grateful for the opportunity to comment on the proposed Bill. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Stoke-on-Trent City Council is a unitary authority which has a retained social housing stock of 19,000 units. The City is ranked as the 16</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> most deprived Local Authority area in the country (out of 326) and has the associated levels of Income and Employment deprivation. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In respect of the specific questions listed by the Joint Committee we do not wish to comment on the majority of these. However, we wish to comment on one of the questions and submit comments about specific provisions proposed in the draft Bill. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 9: Will any or all of the proposals have any significant economic or financial impact?</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do you have any evidence of the impact that will aid the Committee in their scrutiny?</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Section 20 of the draft bill proposes a ‘Reduction of qualifying period for right to buy’, we believe this will make no or minimal impact in the city. Locally, evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that areas such as this will continue to suffer affordability issues regardless of any relaxation to eligibility conditions. There is no additional financial incentive proposed in these changes so the capacity of residents to afford to purchase their home will not have changed. Further evidence of the affordability issue comes from the last changes to the Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> when the regional discount caps were removed. Although the change in discounts raised additional interest from residents about the Right to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Buy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> there was no significant increase in the numbers of Right to Buy sales actually completed.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Section 21 proposes the ‘Removal of power to require preparation of housing strategies’, we are supportive of this approach. In addition to the fact that the powers under the Local Government Act 2003 have not be used there have also been fundamental changes to how housing is financed with the reforms to the Housing Revenue Account. With the housing debt being transferred to the local level it appears right that there should be a reduction in the oversight role allowed for in the LGA 2003. It is for the local housing entities, with local democratic oversight, that need to ensure they have relevant strategies and business planning in place not for a Secretary of State.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Rob Bowler</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Housing Enabling Officer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Housing Services Division</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">People Directorate</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>